720770f-a.title: Manhattan: Lafayette Street - Prince Street
720770f-a.text:
Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from Prince Street, sho:ing the
street under construction after the demolition of buildings which formerly
stood there. The construction of the street necessitated the razing of
many buildings in a northerly direction from Elm Street which terminated
slightly south of Jersey Street, to Lafayette Place which commenced at
Great Jones Street. The new street was named Lafayette Street several
years later.
October 4, 1900.
Board of Transportation Photograph.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
william B. Parsons Collection.

720771f-a.title: Manhattan: Lafayette Street - Prince Street
720771f-a.text:
Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from but not including Prince
Street, showing the street under construction after the demolition of
buildings which formerly stood there. The construction of the street
necessitated the razing of many buildings in a northerly direction from
Elm Street which terminated slightly south of Jersey Street, to Lafayette
Place which commenced at Great Jones Street. The new street was named
Lafayette Street several years later.
September 5, 1900.
Board of Transportation Photograph.

722662f-a.title: Manhattan: Prince Street - Lafayette Street
722662f-a.text:
(1)
63 to 67 Prince Street, north side, west from Lafayette (Elm)
to Crosby Streets, showing at the N.W. corner of Lafayette Street,
No. 63 Prince Street, the house where President Monroe died in 1831.
About July 1926 it was moved to No. 95 Crosby Street, a point on the
east side of the street and south of ~rince Street. During same,it
became damaged and was gone in May 1928.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
(2)
A close-up of the entmances to Nos. 63 and 65.
1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
A view showing Lafayette Street in the foreground. Shown on the
left are the sides and rears of No. 62, a 1-story shack at the corner
(S.W.) and No. 64 a 4-story building. Across the background appear
the upper portions of lofts on Crosby Street, north of Prince Street.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
